<subSubSection pageId="42" pageNumber="43" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,477,903]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,477,503]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Tube white, thin. Branchial crown with 9–10 radioles per lobe; radiole tip not inflated. Opercular peduncle or operculum absent. Thorax with seven chaetigers. Collar with fin-and-blade chaetae, with proximal denticulate expansion separate of distal limbate zone (
<figureCitation box="[835,939,557,583]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="43.[151,255,1796,1820]" captionTargetBox="[268,1321,198,1766]" captionTargetId="figure-135@43.[265,1325,194,1770]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 10. A–D: Pyrgopolon ctenactis, from Baja California Sur, UMAR-Poly 107. A–B, operculum, lateral and aboral views. C: Pyrgopolon ctenactis, from Oaxaca, UMAR-Poly 93. C, operculum, lateral view. D: Pyrgopolon ctenactis, from Guerrero, UMAR-Poly 108. D, operculum, lateral view. E: Rhodopsis pusilla, from Bermuda, USNM 118145, neotype. E, operculum, lateral view. F–G: Salmacina chilensis, from Chile. F–G, collar chaetae, lateral view and detail. H–J: Salmacina tribranchiata, from Sinaloa. H, anterior part, dorsal view. I, collar chaeta. J, “Apomatus” chaeta. K: Semivermilia pomatostegoides, from Tripoli (Mediterranean). K, operculum, lateral view. (Fig. E, redrawn from Ben-Eliahu &amp; ten Hove, 1989. Figs F–G, redrawn from Gallardo, 1969. Fig. K, redrawn from Zibrowius, 1969)." pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Fig. 10F</figureCitation>
), with numerous teeth (
<figureCitation box="[1215,1324,557,583]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="43.[151,255,1796,1820]" captionTargetBox="[268,1321,198,1766]" captionTargetId="figure-135@43.[265,1325,194,1770]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 10. A–D: Pyrgopolon ctenactis, from Baja California Sur, UMAR-Poly 107. A–B, operculum, lateral and aboral views. C: Pyrgopolon ctenactis, from Oaxaca, UMAR-Poly 93. C, operculum, lateral view. D: Pyrgopolon ctenactis, from Guerrero, UMAR-Poly 108. D, operculum, lateral view. E: Rhodopsis pusilla, from Bermuda, USNM 118145, neotype. E, operculum, lateral view. F–G: Salmacina chilensis, from Chile. F–G, collar chaetae, lateral view and detail. H–J: Salmacina tribranchiata, from Sinaloa. H, anterior part, dorsal view. I, collar chaeta. J, “Apomatus” chaeta. K: Semivermilia pomatostegoides, from Tripoli (Mediterranean). K, operculum, lateral view. (Fig. E, redrawn from Ben-Eliahu &amp; ten Hove, 1989. Figs F–G, redrawn from Gallardo, 1969. Fig. K, redrawn from Zibrowius, 1969)." pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Fig. 10G</figureCitation>
). All thoracic chaetigers (except collar segment) with “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Benedict" authorityYear="1887" box="[710,836,597,623]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Apomatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">Apomatus</taxonomicName>
” chaetae. Thoracic uncini saw shaped, with eight rows of teeth and two teeth in each row. Abdomen with 36 chaetigers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,477,903]" box="[198,1116,677,703]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
